# --- Medium auth ---
#
# Medium has TWO auth layers; we support both.
#
# 1) Integration Token (WRITES: publish posts)
#    Legacy endpoint: https://api.medium.com/v1/
#    Token: https://medium.com/me/settings  →  "Integration tokens"
#    (Note: Medium stopped issuing new tokens ~2023 — if you never generated
#     one, the write path will 401.)
#
# MEDIUM_INTEGRATION_TOKEN=2...
#
# 2) sid cookie (READS: posts, responses, claps, feed, user stats)
#    Dashboard uses undocumented GraphQL at https://medium.com/_/graphql
#    Cookie 'sid' from medium.com.
#
# MEDIUM_SID=1:...
# MEDIUM_UID=your-user-id
# MEDIUM_USERNAME=yourhandle
#
# 3) xsrf + cf_clearance (DASHBOARD WRITES: post_response, clap, draft, publish)
#    Required to call medium.com/_/api/* and any GraphQL *mutation*. Grab them
#    from devtools (Application → Cookies → medium.com) the same way you grabbed
#    sid. cf_clearance only matters when Cloudflare challenges your IP.
#
# MEDIUM_XSRF=1b9d23c29032
# MEDIUM_CF_CLEARANCE=h2dUanH6mJKtzENXT_4...
#
# 4) Public RSS path needs NO credentials
#    list_posts/get_post/get_post_content default to medium.com/feed/@{user}
#    when --source auto (default) and the requested limit fits. Set
#    MEDIUM_USERNAME so the client knows whose feed to read.
#
# Override path to mcp.json (defaults to ~/.cursor/mcp.json)
# MEDIUM_OPS_MCP_PATH=/Users/you/.cursor/mcp.json
#
# --- LLM (only needed for `reply bulk/review/auto` and `auto daemon`) ---
#
# PRIMARY (recommended): MCP-native. No env vars needed. Install the MCP server:
#   medium-ops mcp install cursor
# and your host LLM does the drafting via propose_reply / confirm_reply.
#
# SECONDARY: subprocess to a host CLI. Auto-detected from PATH
# (claude / cursor-agent / codex). Override the command with:
# MEDIUM_OPS_LLM_CMD="claude --print"
# # use "{prompt}" placeholder if your CLI takes the prompt as arg:
# MEDIUM_OPS_LLM_CMD="my-cli --prompt {prompt}"
